{"key":"processedPost-10056205","value":{"id":10056205,"first":10055756,"last":11247289,"when":1238203596,"utime":"03/28/09 04:26 AM","content":"The pillow case method has to be the worst possible pasteurization procedure, and is messy to boot.&nbsp; <br /><br />Mix all your substrate ingredients except the verm together and bring to field capacity.&nbsp; Next, hydrate the verm to field capacity, and then mix it into the previously hydrated manure/coir/etc.&nbsp; I'd suggest verm at up to 50% by volume of your substrate mix, since cow manure can be quite muddy without the verm.&nbsp; Use gypsum at up to ten percent, but at least 5%.(just eyeball it.&nbsp; One handful of gypsum for each 20 handfuls of substrate mix)<br /><br />Load into quart jars and pasteurize in a large pot of water on the stove.&nbsp; You'll probably want to bring the water to a boil for the first ten minutes or so.&nbsp; When your thermometer reads 140F in the center of one of the jars, shut off the stove for a few minutes, since the temp in the jars will continue to rise.&nbsp; Maintain 140F to 160F for one hour by manipulating your stove setting.&nbsp; You'll have to babysit it the first time or two you use this method, but then you'll have the routine down and can just repeat it after that.<br />RR","title":"Re: Need Help Pasturizing Black Kow","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}